    <h2>5. Bakery Dough: Bread, Pizza, Pav, and Naan</h2>

    <p>Bakery doughs are fundamentally different from atta dough. Bread, pizza, pav, and naan doughs all require significant gluten development — the dough needs to be kneaded until it reaches a smooth, elastic, windowpane-passing stage. This requires a machine that can work the dough aggressively enough to align the gluten proteins, which is why spiral mixers and fork kneaders dominate bakery production.</p>

    <h3>Bread Dough</h3>
    <p>Standard white bread dough (60–65% hydration) is the classic spiral mixer application. The spiral hook develops gluten efficiently, and the two-speed operation allows you to incorporate ingredients on slow speed before switching to fast speed for full development. A typical mixing cycle is 3–4 minutes on slow speed followed by 8–12 minutes on fast speed. For a <strong>dough mixer for bakery</strong> focused on bread, spiral mixers are the clear winner.</p>

    <h3>Pizza Dough</h3>
    <p>Pizza dough varies widely — Neapolitan pizza dough is high-hydration (60–70%), needs moderate gluten development, and benefits from cold fermentation. Thick-crust pizza dough is stiffer and needs more aggressive kneading. For Neapolitan-style pizza, a fork kneader is actually superior to a spiral mixer because it preserves the extensible, stretchy character of the dough. For high-volume pizza chains producing standard dough, spiral mixers are more practical.</p>

    <h3>Pav Dough</h3>
    <p>Pav (the soft bread rolls that are a staple of Indian bakeries) requires a dough that is enriched with milk, butter, and sugar. Enriched doughs put more strain on the mixer motor because the fats coat the flour proteins and slow down gluten development. A spiral mixer with a strong motor (at least 1.5 HP for 20kg capacity) is ideal. Many Indian bakeries produce 500–2,000 pav daily, requiring a 20–40kg spiral mixer.</p>

    <h3>Naan Dough</h3>
    <p>Naan dough is a medium-hydration, yogurt-enriched dough that needs moderate kneading. For tandoor restaurants producing naan in large quantities, a medium-capacity atta kneading machine or a spiral mixer both work well. The key is not to over-knead — naan dough should be soft and slightly sticky, not tight and elastic like bread dough.</p>

